### Instant Loading States

The `loading.js` file creates a Suspense boundary that shows a fallback UI while the page component loads:

```jsx
// app/dashboard/loading.js
export default function Loading() {
  return (
    <div className="spinner">
      <p>Loading dashboard...</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

The page content streams in once it's ready, replacing the loading state automatically.

### How It Works

Next.js wraps `page.js` and nested children in a Suspense boundary. The `loading.js` component serves as the `fallback` prop:

```jsx
// Internally, Next.js does something like:
<Layout>
  <Suspense fallback={<Loading />}>
    <Page />
  </Suspense>
</Layout>
```

### Streaming SSR

With streaming, the server sends HTML in chunks as it becomes available. Users see content sooner instead of waiting for the full page:

```jsx
// app/dashboard/page.js — Data-dependent component
async function getData() {
  const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/slow-data');
  return res.json();
}

export default async function Dashboard() {
  const data = await getData(); // This causes the loading state

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Dashboard</h1>
      <pre>{JSON.stringify(data, null, 2)}</pre>
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Granular Suspense Boundaries

For more control, use Suspense directly:

```jsx
import { Suspense } from 'react';

async function SlowComponent() {
  const data = await fetch('https://api.example.com/slow').then(r => r.json());
  return <div>{data.content}</div>;
}

function Fallback() {
  return <div className="skeleton">Loading...</div>;
}

export default function Page() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Page Title</h1>
      <Suspense fallback={<Fallback />}>
        <SlowComponent />
      </Suspense>
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Route Group Loading

Place `loading.js` at any segment level to show loading UI for that route and its children.

codeExample:
// app/posts/loading.js
export default function PostsLoading() {
  return (
    <div className="grid gap-4">
      {[1, 2, 3].map((i) => (
        <div key={i} className="animate-pulse h-24 bg-gray-200 rounded"></div>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}

// app/posts/page.js
async function getPosts() {
  return fetch('https://api.example.com/posts').then(r => r.json());
}

export default async function PostsPage() {
  const posts = await getPosts();
  return (
    <div>
      {posts.map(p => (
        <div key={p.id} className="p-4 border">{p.title}</div>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
